==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bērō-'', from Indo-European ''*bher-'' ‘carry’.
Cognate with Old High German ''beran'', Old Saxon ''beran'', Old Norse [[bera]] (Icelandic [[bera]]), Gothic [[𐌱𐌰𐌹𐍂𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root was also the source of Armenian [[berem]], Old Irish [[biru]], Greek [[φέρω]], Latin [[fero]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'beran/

===Verb===
'''beran''' (class IV strong: '''bierþ'''/'''birþ''' ‘he bears’; '''bær''' ‘he bore’; '''bǣron''' ‘they bore’; '''ġeboren''' ‘borne’)
# to [[bear]], [[carry]]
# to [[wear]]
# to [[sustain]], [[support]]
# to bring forth, [[produce]], give birth

